Start Jupyter notebook on Nova on demand.¶

You can start Jupyter notebook on Nova on demand. This will allow you to run Jupyter notebook on the server and access it from your local machine.

  1. Go to the Nova OnDemand and login
  2. Under the "Interactive Apps" tab, click on "Jupyter Notebook", request desired resources and click "Launch"
  3. Wait for the job to start and click on the "Connect to Jupyter" button

Plotting and Visualization¶

Visualization is a key component of data analysis, allowing you to explore data and communicate results. We have briefly touched on visualization. Now we will go over the basics in more depth. There are two libraries that are commonly used for plotting. Matplotlib is the most popular Python library for creating static, animated, and interactive visualizations in Python. Seaborn builds on Matplotlib, allowing us to create more attractive and statistically meaningful graphs with better defaults and built-in support for complex relationships. So, although we are learning about Seaborn, we will still use Pandas to load and manipulate the data, matplotlib for additional customization, and seaborn for plotting.

Getting Started¶

To begin, we need to import the necessary libraries. We want Pandas to manipulate the dataframes, and matplotlib to provide us extended plot functionality. Then we also load seaborn so that we can make pretty plots. Just like pandas was abbreviated on import (pd), common conventions apply for seaborn and matplotlib

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

First, we will set change some default settings to our specification (and make the plots look better!). Let's increase the resolution (dpi) to 200, increase the size to 10 x 5 inches, and decrease the font to 8 points (squeeze more characters in!).

In [16]:
plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 200
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 10,5
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 8})

Basic plotting¶

Let's first begin by creating a scatterplot from the iris data. In addition to specifying which columns belong to the x and y axes, we also want to color the data by species.

In [7]:
sns.scatterplot(data=iris, x='sepal_length', y='sepal_width', hue='species');

We can also create boxplot of the data

In [8]:
sns.boxplot(data=iris, x='species', y='sepal_length');

Violin plot of the iris dataset¶

In [9]:
sns.violinplot(data=iris, x='species', y='sepal_length');

This dataset contains information of all the passengers aboard the RMS Titanic, including some demographic and survival data. First, let's check the number of passengers in each class.

In [12]:
sns.countplot(data=titanic, x='class');

We can plot these classes by survival:

In [13]:
sns.countplot(data=titanic, x='class', hue='survived');

Alternatively, we can group survival by sex instead of class.

In [14]:
sns.countplot(data=titanic, x='survived', hue='sex');

We can check this information for other variables as well. Here we can see survival by where they embarked (perhaps a proxy for class?).

In [11]:
sns.countplot(data=titanic, x='survived', hue='embark_town');

If we want to see overall survival rate, we can plot the data without any groups (i.e., hue)

In [16]:
sns.countplot(x='survived', data=titanic);

Other informational plots can be created using the sns.catplot function. (Here, catplot is generic way of saying this is a categorical plot. Other categorical plots include:

  • strip: A scatter plot where one of the variables is categorical.
  • swarm: Similar to strip plots but with adjustments to avoid overlapping points.
  • box: Box plots that display the distribution of data.
  • violin: Violin plots that combine a box plot with a kernel density estimate.
  • bar: Bar plots summarizing the central tendency of the data.
  • point: Point plots to show estimated values and their confidence intervals.

If you don't remember the shorthand for it (i.e., .boxplot()), you can always use the kind command within catplot. Here we will make a boxplot with fare on the y-axis (instead of count) and we will use sns.catplot(kind="box") to make our boxplot.

In [15]:
sns.catplot(data=titanic, x='class', y='fare', hue = 'class', kind='box');

Seaborn can easily make more complicated plots. For example, we can easily make a pairplot, which generates scatter plots for all pairwise combinations of numerical features and places them with density plots (on the diagonal). We will use the iris dataset to demonstrate this since it is small.

In [17]:
sns.pairplot(iris, hue='species');

Seaborn has different plot types: relational plots, distribution plots, and categorical plots.

Because our earlier plots were all one type (and subtype), we were easily able to plot our data. If, however, we want to combine plots of difference types, we will have to make panels for each of the plots using a combination of plt and sns. Here we will combine a scatterplot and a boxplot in the same figure.

In [19]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))  # define a figure with 2 axes arrayed as 1 row, 2 columns

# Scatterplot on the first subplot
sns.scatterplot(data=iris, x="petal_length", y="petal_width", hue="species", ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title("Scatterplot of Petal Length vs. Width")

# Boxplot on the second subplot
sns.boxplot(data=iris, x="species", y="petal_length", ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title("Boxplot of Petal Length by Species")

# Show the plots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Compare that to the minimal code required for a single type of plot, but split into facets.

In [23]:
sns.catplot(x="embark_town", col="survived", data=titanic, kind="count", hue="embark_town")
Out[23]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x14878b615450>
